# Multiplayer (optional). Copy to `.env` and fill in from your Supabase project.
# Only Realtime is used — no tables — so the free tier is plenty. When these are
# ABSENT the Multiplayer menu is hidden and the solo game is unaffected.
#
# Uses Supabase's NEW API keys (Project → Settings → API Keys):
#   - PUBLISHABLE key `sb_publishable_...`  → client-safe, goes here.
#   - SECRET key      `sb_secret_...`       → server-only. DO NOT put it here:
#     VITE_* vars are inlined into the shipped browser bundle, which would leak
#     it. This client-only app never needs the secret key.
#
# On Vercel: add the same vars under Project → Settings → Environment Variables
# (baked in at build time — redeploy after a change). For Electron, set them in
# the shell before `npm run dist`.

VITE_SUPABASE_URL=
VITE_SUPABASE_PUBLISHABLE_KEY=

# TURN relay (OPTIONAL). WebRTC needs TURN to connect peers behind symmetric /
# carrier-grade NAT (mobile, some corporate/home networks); without it those
# matches freeze at WAITING. A FREE public TURN (Metered Open Relay) is built in
# by default — no signup — so leave ALL of the below blank to use it. It's
# best-effort / rate-limited, so for reliability use your own (options below).
#
# SECURITY: never put a provider API *secret* (e.g. Metered's `sb_secret`-style
# REST key) in a VITE_ var — Vite inlines VITE_* into the shipped browser bundle.
# Pick ONE of the two approaches:
#
# (A) PREFERRED — ephemeral creds, NO secret in the client. Point this at an
#     endpoint that mints short-lived ICE creds (Metered's credentials API keyed
#     by a PUBLIC api key, or your own serverless fn holding the secret). The
#     app fetches ICE servers from it at runtime; a leaked ephemeral cred expires.
# VITE_TURN_ICE_URL=https://<app>.metered.live/api/v1/turn/credentials?apiKey=<PUBLIC_API_KEY>
#
# (B) STATIC credential pair (username + credential). Simpler, but the pair ships
#     in the bundle and can be extracted to relay someone else's traffic
#     (bandwidth theft, capped by your quota) — it is NOT an account secret, but
#     (A) is safer. VITE_TURN_URL may list multiple transports (udp/tcp/tls).
# VITE_TURN_URL=turn:your.turn.host:3478,turn:your.turn.host:443?transport=tcp
# VITE_TURN_USERNAME=
# VITE_TURN_CREDENTIAL=
